    <p>Interactive articles also communicate a single idea or concept using multiple representations. The same information represented in different forms can have different impact. For example, in mathematics often a single object has both an algebraic, notional representation and a geometric representation. A clear example of this is the definition of a circle [cite distill augmenting]. Both are useful, inform one another, and lead to different ways of thinking. This is the Multimedia Principle in action: people learn better from words and pictures rather than words or pictures alone [cite]. Interactive article examples that demonstrate this include publications’ political election coverage that break down the same outcome in multiple ways, for example, by voter demographics, geographical location, and historical perspective [cite CNN, 538, nytimes, how many others?]</p>

    <p>
      <d-figure class="video-d-figure" id="sanderson2018visualizing"></d-figure>
      However, multiple representations should not simply repeat information for repetition’s sake. The Redundancy Principle states that eliminating redundant material and avoiding narration and “identical” text leads to better learning [Hoffman, B.(2006), Encyclopedia]. Therefore, interactive articles should not let the text be redundant with the graphics, but rather complement them through, for example through highlighting main messages. Popular video creators such as 3Blue1Brown [cite] and Primer [cite] exemplify these principles by using rich animation and narration to investigate complex topics. While these videos are praised for their approachability and rich exposition, one radical extension from traditional video content is also incorporating user input into the video while narration plays. One series of these interactive videos for “Visualizing Quaternions” lets a reader listen to narration of a live animation on screen, but at any time the reader can take control of the video and drive the animation while still listening to the narration [cite].
    </p>

