    <h3 id="reducing-cognitive-load">Reducing Cognitive Load</h3>
    
    <p>Authors must calibrate the detail at which to discuss ideas and content to their readers expertise and interest to not overload them. When topics become multifaceted and complex, a balance must be struck between a high-level overview of a topic and its lower-level details. One ubiquitous interaction technique used to prevent a cognitive overload within a reader is “details-on-demand.” Classically, from a data analysis perspective, this technique allows users to select parts of a dataset to be shown in more detail while maintaining an overview of the whole space. This is particularly useful when a change of view is not required, so that users can inspect elements of interest on a point-by-point basis in the context of the whole [craft2005beyond]. Below we highlight areas where details-on-demand has been successfully applied to reduce the amount of information present within an interface at once.</p>

    <p>[which videos / interactive figure to include here?]</p>

    <p>Data visualization. Details-on-demand is core to information visualization, and concludes the seminal Visual Information-Seeking Mantra: “Overview first, zoom and filter, then details-on-demand” [shneiderman1996eyes]. Successful visualizations not only provide the base representations and techniques for these three steps, but also bridge the gaps between them [keim2002information]. In practice, the solidified standard for details-on-demand in data visualization manifests as a tooltip, typically summoned on a cursor mouseover, that presents extra information in an overlay. Given that data often contains multiple attributes, tooltips can show the other attributes that are not currently encoded in a visualization. [need example]</p>

    <p>Illustration. Details-on-demand is also used in illustrations, interactive textbooks, and museum exhibits, where highlighted segments of a figure can be selected to display additional information about the particular segment. For example, in “How does the eye work?” readers can select segments of an anatomical diagram of the human eye to learn more about specific regions, e.g., rods and cones [ala2018how]. Another example is Earth Primer, an interactive textbook on tablets that allows readers to inspect the Earth’s interior, surface, and biomes [gingold2015earth]. Each illustration contains segments the reader can tap to learn and explore in depth.</p>

    <p>Mathematical notation. Formal mathematics, a historically static medium, can benefit from details-on-demand, for example, to elucidate a reader with intuition about a particular algebraic term or present a geometric interpretation of an equation. For example, in “Colorized Math Equations,” the Fourier Transform equation is presented in both mathematical notation and plain text, but the two are linked through a mouseover that highlights which term in the equation corresponds to which word in the text [azad2017colorized]. Another example that visualizes mathematics and computation is the “Image Kernels” tutorial where a reader can mouseover a real image and observe the effect and exact computation for applying a filter over the image. This operation, called a convolution, is at the core of convolutional neural network architectures that have recently driven machine learning progress. Instead of writing down long arithmetic sums, the interface allows readers to quickly see the summation operation’s terms and output [powell2015image].</p>

    <p>Text. While not as pervasive as other types of information, text documents and other longform textual mediums have also experimented with letting readers choose a variable level of detail to read. This idea was explored as early as the 1960s in StretchText, a hypertext feature that allows a reader to reveal a more descriptive or exhaustive explanation of something by expanding or contracting the content in place [nelson1967stretchtext]. This idea has resurfaced in recent examples, including the “On Variable Level-of-detail Documents” demo [beecroft2019on], a PhD thesis turned interactive article [cite], and the call for proposals of the Parametric Press [conlen2018parametric]. One challenge that has limited this technique’s adoption is the burden it places on authors to write multiple versions of their content. For other examples of details-on-demand for text, such as application in code documentation, see this small collection of examples [basques2018ui].</p>

    <p>Previewing content. Details-on-demand can also be used as a method for previewing content without committing to another interaction. For example, when hovering over another hyperlink on Wikipedia, a preview card is shown that can contain an image and brief description; this gives readers a quick preview of the topic without clicking through and loading a new page [wikipedia2018preview]. This idea is also not new: work from human-computer interaction explored fluid links [zellweger1998fluid, zellweger2002reading] within hypertext that present information about a particular topic in a location that does not obscure the source material. Both older and modern preview techniques use perceptually-based animation and simple tooltips to ensure their interactions are natural and lightweight feeling to readers [zellweger1998fluid]. Besides these examples, details-on-demand has become a ubiquitous design pattern, from image previews when scrubbing a video, to visualizing approximate query results in big data analysis using progressive refinement [rauschenbach1998progressive, rauschenbach1999demand, moritz2017trust].</p>


    <h3 id="personalization">Personalization</h3>
    
    <p>Content personalization, automatically modifying text and multimedia based on reader’s individual features or input (e.g., demographics or location), is a technique that has been shown to increase engagement and learning within readers [cordova1996intrinsic] and support behavioral change [di2006authoring]. The PersaLog system gives developers tools to build such content and presents guidelines for personalization based on user research from practicing journalists [adar2017persalog]. Other work has shown that “personalized spatial analogies,” presenting distance measurements in regions where readers are geographically familiar with, help people more concretely understand new distance measurements within news stories [kim2016generating].</p>

    <p>
      <d-figure class="video-d-figure" id="popovich2018how"></d-figure>
      Personalization alone has also been used as the center of interactive articles. Both “How Much Hotter Is Your Hometown Than When You Were Born?” [popovich2018how] and “Human Terrain” [daniels2018human] use location to drive stories relating to climate change and population densities respectively. Other examples ask for explicit reader input, such as a story that visualizes a reader’s net worth to challenge a reader’s assumptions if they are wealthy or not (relative to the greater population) [quealy2019are], or predicting a reader’s political party affiliation [chinoy2010quiz]. Another example is the interactive scatterplot featured in “Find Out If Your Job Will Be Automated” [whitehouse2017find]. Here, professions are plotted to inspect their likelihood of being automated against their average annual wage. The article encourages readers to use the search bar to type in their own profession to highlight it against the others.
    </p>

    <p>[VIDEO: human terrain example, nytimes how hot, or bloomberg job automation?]</p>

    <p>An interactive medium has the potential to offer readers an experience other than static, linear text. Non-linear stories, where an operator can choose their own path through the content, have the potential to provide a more personalized experience and focus on areas of user interest [sizemore2011interactive]. For example, the BBC has used this technique in both online articles [cite] and in a recent episode of Click [cite], a technology focused news television program. Non-linear stories present challenges for authors, as they must consider the myriad possible paths through the content, and consider the different possible experiences that the audience would have when pursuing different branches.</p>

    <p>
      <d-figure class="video-d-figure" id="matuschak2019quantum"></d-figure>
      Another technique interactive articles often use is segmenting content into small pieces to be read in-between or alongside other graphics. While we have already discussed cognitive load theory, the Segmenting Theory, the idea that complex lessons are broken into smaller, bit-sized parts [Clark & Mayer 2011 e-learning], also supports personalization within interactive articles. Providing a reader the ability to play, pause, and scrub content allows the reader to move at their own speed, comprehending the information at a speed that works best from them. Segmenting also engages a reader’s essential processing without overloading their cognitive system [Clark & Mayer 2011 e-learning]. Multiple studies have been conducted showing that learners perform better when using sementing information, whether it be only within an animation [Dow, & Mayer 2003 microworld] or within a interface with textual descriptions [cite Mayer, Mathias, and Wetzell (2002) pictorial]. One excellent example of using segmentation and animation to personalize content delivery is “A Visual Introduction to Machine Learning,” which introduces fundamental concepts within machine learning in bite-sized pieces, while transforming a single dataset into a trained machine learning model [cite].
    </p>

    <h2 id="critical-reflections">Critical Reflections</h2>

    <p>While it has never been easier for writers to share their ideas online, current publishing tools largely support only static authoring and don’t offer take full advantage of the fact that the web is a dynamic medium. We want that to change. [TK sentence about things we have done before parametric … idyll, dim. reduction, kde article?, 538 work?] </p>

    <p>To explore these ideas further, we, the authors of this article, together with a group of designers, programmers, and researchers, created the Parametric Press: an annually published digital magazine that showcases the expository power that interactive dynamic media can have when used effectively. In late 2018, we invited writers to respond to a call for proposals for our first issue focusing on exploring scientific and technological phenomena that stand to shape society at large. </p>

    <p>We sought to cover topics that would benefit from using the interactive or otherwise dynamic capabilities of the web. Given the challenges of authoring interactive articles, we didn’t ask authors to submit fully developed pieces. Instead, we accepted idea submissions, and collaborated with the authors to develop the issue, offering technical, design, and editorial assistance collectively.</p>

    <p>We see the Parametric Press as a crucial connection between the often distinct worlds of research and practice. The Press serves as a platform through which to operationalize the theories put forth by education, journalism, and HCI researchers. Tools like Idyll which are designed in a research setting need to be validated and battle tested to ensure that they are of practical use; the Press facilitates this by allowing us to study its use in a real-world setting, by authors who are personally motivated to complete their task of constructing a high-quality interactive article, and care about the tooling being used as a secondary concern, if at all.</p>

    <p>The act of practicing that which you study, becoming a para-researcher, also allows one to identify hidden concerns that haven’t been discussed by academic researchers, or which researchers have not deemed worthy of study.</p>

    <p>From its inception, one of the objectives of the Parametric Press is to showcase the new forms of media and publishing that are possible with tools available today, and inspire others to create their own dynamic writings. To that end, we made available all of the software that runs the site, including reusable components, custom data visualizations, and the publishing engine itself. To address interactive content archival, we have set up a system to publish a digital archive of all of our articles at the time that they are first published to the site. We hope to show how digital works such as ours can published confidently knowing that they will be preserved indefinitely.</p>

    <h3>Theory x. Practice</h3>

    <div id="research-x-practice" style="width: 100%"></div>

    <h2 id="challenges">The Challenges of Interactive Articles in Practice</h2>

    <p>If interactive articles provide clear benefits over other mediums for communicating complex ideas, then why aren’t there more of them? Unfortunately, creating interactive articles today is quite challenging. A successful interactive article requires combining diverse editorial, design, and programming skills. Furthermore, authoring interactive articles often takes significantly more time and effort than a static article, blog post, or even academic publication [cite distill github repo] (footnote: As a proxy, see the number of commits on an example Distill article [cite]). Because of these practical challenges, many interactive articles are created by a collective team consisting of multiple members with specialized skills.</p>

    <p>Regarding technology, relatively few tools exist that support the development of such articles. Most interactive articles are created using general purpose web-development frameworks which, while expressive, can be difficult to work with for authors who aren’t also web developers. Publishing to the web also brings its own challenges: while interactive articles are accessible to anyone with a browser, they are burdened by rapidly changing web technologies that could break interactive content after just a few years. For this reason, easy and accessible interactive article archival is important for authors to know their work can be confidently preserved indefinitely to support continued readership.  Authoring interactive articles also requires designing for a diverse set of devices, for example, ensuring bespoke content can be adapted for desktop and mobile screen sizes with varying connection speeds, since accessing interactive content demands more bandwidth.</p>

    <p>It is also important to remember that not everything needs to be interactive. Authors should consider the audience and context of their work when deciding if use of interactivity would be valuable. In the worst case, interactivity may be distracting to readers or the functionality may go unused, the author having wasted their time implementing it. However, even in a domain where the potential communication improvement is increcremental, at scale (e.g., delivering via the web), interactive articles can still have impact. [cite nielsen book and thread] [TK Multimedia studies actually show large effect sizes for improvement of transfer learning in many cases]</p>

    <p>Besides authoring, there are other non-technical limitations for publishing interactive articles. For example, in non-journalism domains, there is a mis-aligned incentive structure for authoring and publishing interactive content: why should a researcher spend time on an “extra” interactive exposition of their work when they could instead publish more papers, a metric by which their career depends on? While different groups of people seek to maximize their work’s impact, legitimizing interactive artifacts requires buy-in from a collective of communities. [TK feels like there should be one more sentence here]</p>

    <p>How can we help?</p>

    <p>It takes a breadth of skills to author an interactive article. Can we develop new tools to help lower the barrier to entry? While there have been great, practical strides in this direction [cite idyll, apparatus, observable, loopy, webstrates], there is still opportunity for creating tools to design, develop, and evaluate interactive articles in the wild. Specific features include supporting mobile-friendly adaptations of interactive graphics, creating content for different platforms besides just the web, and tools that allow people to create interactive content without code. Extending further, could future authoring tools also close the loop on publishing and evaluating interactive content in the wild? For example, collecting and visualizing graphic-specific interaction logs or usage statistics to inform the author of their design decisions.</p>

    <p>To meet these challenges has emerged a diverse community exploring and experimenting with what interactive articles could be. The Explorable Explanations [cite explorables] community is a “disorganized ‘movement’ of artists, coders & educators who want to reunite play and learning.” The hub contains 170+ interactive articles on topics ranging from art, natural sciences, social sciences, journalism, and civics. The curious can also find tools, tutorials, and meta-discussion around learning, play, and representations. Explorables also hosted a mixed in-person and online Jam [cite https://explorabl.es/jam/]: a community-based sprint focused on creating new explorable explanations. </p>

